title: Grateful Dead Live at McNichols Sports Arena on 1990-12-12
lineage: Dat (Sony D8) -> Samplitude Professional v11.1 -> FLAC
description:
Set 1

Touch Of Gray-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Candyman, Walkin' Blues, Loose Lucy, Mexicali Blues-> Maggie's Farm, Queen Jane Approximately, Deal

Set 2

China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Looks Like Rain, Iko Iko, Dark Star-> Terrapin Station-> Drums-> Jam-> All Along The Watchtower-> Stella Blue-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: The Weight

reviews.review_text: I was There Was living in Boulder at the time. Saw all three shows for this run. The Loose Lucy is a best ever quality Deal is a smash mouth version as well. The second set pre-drums in quite a delight. Iko-Dark Star-Terrapin, hard to complain about that. After drums is rather formulated but well played. I remember thinking that since I was going to be there for  all three shows that it was a change to see Throwing Stones-NFA the first night. Typically during three night runs it seems the endings were Sugar Magnolia, Lovelight then the Throwin-NFA the final night. So while it was predictable at least the prediction came the first night. Check out 12-13 the next night, another very well played show.  At the show anyway Phil’s Bass was much louder on the 13th. And they ended the show with Box of rain which was nice too.

6 song pre drums China>Rider>LL Rain>Dark Star>Iko>Terrapin

Defiantly some extra effort going on during this show.

CM's copy is certainly the best sound quality.

Nice to see that the band is still playing and not going through the motions like so rigorously accused post Brent. 

Denver and the whole Colorado area always brings out that special X-factor that the Dead would always surprise their audiences to no end with. 

McNichols was huge and characterless but atleast this SBD lets us forget about that old knocked down venue and just focus on the music.

Setlist wise this could be one of the better Colorado shows the Dead ever played. Its obvious they gave their all on this run, at a very vulnerable moment of their existence. Along with the last two MSG shows, this is the best Vince/Bruce show of 1990. Just really sincere and everybody is present both bodily and spiritually.

Memorable moment One thing about this show I'll always remember. Was seated way up high with a bird's-eye view of the whole crowd. During Iko Iko I surveyed the entire place trying to find ONE body that was motionless -- could find NOT ONE in a sold out crowd (I think) of 20,000 plus. EVERYONE was getting down with that incredible groove. What a rush...only at a Grateful Dead concert!

Encore Encore Show is so so...Yes i'm not a post brent guy (like most)
However i think "The weight" on this one was very well done. Bravo...Forever Grateful...RIP JG

Beyond my expectations Deal is huge. Hornsby's  volume is just right. The first set in general is very tight.  China>Rider smokes as usual. Not Fade Away is ripping. 

One of the best post-Mydland shows imo.

jerry light, out of body, out of sight hundreds of us SOULS went into the rafters from Dark Star on
hottest show I ever experienced

1 mile high! First shows I saw w/o Brent and some of my last.
Can't believe it was 25 years ago! Actually listening to Healy source right now which sounds great! I'll listen to Charlie's in a bit!

Best night of the 3 really; Aiko/Dark Star/Terrapin was pretty epic, Jerry sounding great, trippy noodling during DS. Maggie's Farm in first hot too. Good times
